General Part¶

Question 1¶

a.¶

Firstly, let us write out the component-wise product $\boldsymbol{T} = \boldsymbol{L'}\boldsymbol{U'}$, where $i = 2, ..., N$, \begin{align*} t_{1,1} &= l'_{1,1} \\ t_{i, i-1} &= l'_{i, i-1} \\ t_{i, i} &= l'_{i, i-1} \cdot u'_{i-1, i} + l'_{i, i} \\ t_{i-1, i} &= l'_{i-1, i-1} \cdot u'_{i-1, i}. \end{align*}

Now that we have these expressions, we can define the form of $\boldsymbol{L'}$ and $\boldsymbol{U'}$ analogously to eq. (1.7) of the lecture notes, \begin{equation*} l'_{1, 1} = t_{1, 1}; \; \text{for} \; i = 2, ..., N, \; u'_{i-1, i} = \frac{t_{i-1, 1}}{l'_{i-1, i-1}}; \; l'_{i, i-1} = t_{i, i-1}; \; l'_{i, i} = t_{i, i} - l'_{i, i-1} \cdot u'_{i-1, i}. \end{equation*}

We still perform the forward subsitution as $\boldsymbol{L'}\boldsymbol{y} = \boldsymbol{b}$ as in eq. (1.8) in the lecture notes, \begin{equation*} y_1 = \frac{b_1}{l'_{1, 1}}; \; \text{for} \; i = 2, ..., N \; y_i = \frac{b_i}{l'_{i, i}} - l'_{i, i-1}y_{i-1}. \end{equation*}

Finally, for the back subsitution step $\boldsymbol{U}\boldsymbol{x} = \boldsymbol{y}$ we again follow the same procedure as in eq. (1.9) of the lecture notes, \begin{equation*} x_N = y_N; \; \text{for} \; i = N, ..., 2 \; x_{i-1} = y_{i-1} - u'_{i-1, i}x_i. \end{equation*}

b.¶

Case I

We can naively solve this system by writing out the two linear equations, \begin{align*} x_1 + x_2 &= 1 \\ x_1 + (1 + 10^{-10})x_2 &= 1. \end{align*}

Filling in one into the other yields, \begin{align*} 1 - x_2 + (1 + 10^{-10})x_2 &= 1 \\ 10^{-10}x_2 &= 0 \\ x_2 &= 0 \\ &\rightarrow x_1 = 1. \end{align*}

So, \begin{equation*} \vec{x} = \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 0\end{pmatrix}. \end{equation*}

Case II

Similarly as above, \begin{align*} x_1 + x_2 &= 1 \\ x_1 + (1 + 10^{-10})x_2 &= 1 + 10^{-10}. \end{align*}

Again, filling in one into the other, \begin{align*} 1 - x_2 + (1 + 10^{-10})x_2 &= 1 \\ 10^{-10}x_2 &= 10^{-10} \\ x_2 &= 1 \\ &\rightarrow x_1 = 0. \end{align*}

So, \begin{equation*} \vec{x} = \begin{pmatrix}0 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}. \end{equation*}

c.¶

Before even having calculated anything I am certain this matrix is ill-conditioned, purely due to the $10^{-10}$ term present. Let us prove this however by computing the eigenvalues of this matrix, \begin{align*} \begin{vmatrix} 1 - \lambda & 1 \\ 1 & 1 + 10^{-10} - \lambda \end{vmatrix} &= 0 \\ (1 - \lambda)(1 + 10^{-10} - \lambda) - 1 &= 0 \\ \lambda^2 -\lambda(2 + 10^{-10}) + 10^{-10} &= 0 \\ \lambda_\pm = \frac{2 + 10^{-10} \pm \sqrt{(2 + 10^{-10})^2 - 4*10^{-10}}}{2} &\\ \lambda_\pm = \frac{2 + 10^{-10} \pm \sqrt{4 + 10^{-20}}}{2}. &\\ \end{align*}

Now, these two eigenvalues turn out to be vastly different from one another, about an expected order of magnitude $10^{-10}$. Now, it doesn't yield anything by writing out these expressions further, nor is it easy and useful to simplify this further. We can however, give the approximate values: \begin{align*} \lambda_{\text{max}} \approx 2; \; \lambda_{\text{min}} \approx 5\cdot 10^{-11}. \end{align*}

Filling in these values into the expression for the condition number yields, \begin{align*} \kappa \approx \frac{2}{5\cdot 10^{-11}} \approx 4\cdot 10^{10}. \end{align*}

Given that $\kappa$ should idealy lie around $1$, to say that this matrix is ill-conditioned is an understatement.

d.¶

What we have here is a nearly singular matrix ($\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1\end{bmatrix}$ is a fully singular matrix, and we are only $10^{-10}$ away from this in only a single element). We have already established that this problem is ill-conditioned, and indeed, when changing the independent variables only slightly (case I to case II), the dependent variable $\vec{x}$ changes dramatically. From the definition of the condition number (eq. (1.13) of the lecture notes), we learn that it is related to the maximum relative error. Given that the condition number is in the order of $10^{10}$ for this problem, and assuming that for the uncertainty $\delta$ of $b$ it holds that $\delta < b$ (which is a more than reasonable assumption), the error is so incredibly large that the solution for $\vec{x}$ is useless.

Now, if $\vec{b}$ were some inputs to a model and $\vec{x}$ the output parameters, we can deduce from what has previously been stated that a tiny change in the input (possibly even rounding errors) will lead to a completely different output of the model. This leads us to conclude that convergence is (nearly) impossible (i.e. we will not find a solution to $\vec{x}$ to a reasonable degree, if at all), or that the problem is ill-conditioned (i.e. the parameters that we need to work with cannot produce a satisfying result).

Question 2¶

a.¶

The implementation that I have written stores the tridiagonal LU decomposition in $3N - 1$ units of memory. This is a little worse than the theoretical $3N - 2$ if we assume that only array elements take memory. The reason for this is that instead of having three arrays, one for the off-diagonal $L$, one for the diagonal $U$ and one for the off-diagonal $U$, I have a 1-D array of length $N - 1$ for $L$, and a 2-D array of length $2 \times N$ for $U$. Since the off-diagonal of $U$ only has $N - 1$ elements, the last element of this 2-D array is always zero, and thus wasted. However, in an actual memory map this method will be more efficient than the three separate arrays, since there is less header data and/or metadata needed to define the arrays.

Now, let us consider the given matrix $T$. From the tridiagonal decomposition (eqs. (1.7) - (1.9) in the lecture notes) we can state the following, \begin{align*} u_{i-1, i} &= t_{i-1, i} = 1 \\ u_{i, i} &= t_{i, i} - l_{i, i-1}u_{i-1,i} \\ &= -2 - u_{i-1, i-1}^{-1} &\quad \text{(filling in the general expression for $l_{i, i-1}$)}\\ l_{i, i-1} &= t_{i, i-1} \cdot u_{i-1, i-1}^{-1} \\ &= -(2 + u_{i-2, i-2}^{-1})^{-1} &\quad \text{(using the found relation for the diagonal of $U$)}\\ &= -(2 + l_{i-1, i-2})^{-1} &\quad \text{(using the general expression stated above, $l_{i, i-1} = ...$)} \end{align*}

Lastly, let us check if these relations are identical to the result we obtain from our written tridiagonal LU decomposition. The Python code used to verify this is found below.

In [58]:
N = 10
diag = -2 * np.ones(N)
off_diag = np.ones(N-1)

# Decompose the matrix
l, u = SparseTridiagonal().decompose(diag, off_diag)

# Compare to the recurrence relations
res_l = l == -1 / (2 + np.roll(l, 1))
res_u = u[0, :] == -2 - 1/np.roll(u[0], 1)

# Check if the recurrence relations hold for i = range(1, N)
if res_l[1:].all() and res_u[1:].all():
    print("The recurrence relations hold.")
else:
    print("The recurrence relations do not agree with the tridiagonal decomposition.")

The recurrence relations hold.

As we can see from the script's result, the recurrence relations hold for $i \in {2, ..., N}$ (in 1-based indexing). The reason that we skip the first index is because for $i = 1$, $l_{i, i-1}$ is not defined (or out of bounds).

The analytical solution to the problem of eq. (3) in the assignment is $f(y) = -\frac{1}{\pi^2} \sin(\pi y)$. This solution, along with the numerical solution is plotted in the figure below. Additionally, the difference between the two is also plotted.

def solve_and_plot_2(y, dy, g, f_ana):
    matrix = SparseTridiagonal()
    matrix.decompose(diag, off_diag)
    f = matrix.solve(dy**2 * g[1:-1])
    f = [0, *f, 0]

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 2*4.8))
    plt.subplot(211)
    plt.plot(y, f, '.', label="Numerical solution")
    plt.plot(y, f_ana, label="Analytical solution")
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel("y")
    plt.ylabel("f")
    plt.subplot(212)
    plt.plot(y, f_ana - f, '.', label=r"$f_{ana} - f$")
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel("y")
    plt.ylabel(r"$\Delta f$")

    return f

N = 101
diag = -2 * np.ones(N-2)
off_diag = np.ones(N-3)

y, dy = np.linspace(0, 1, N, retstep=True)
g = np.sin(np.pi * y)
f_ana = -np.sin(np.pi * y) / np.pi**2

solve_and_plot_2(y, dy, g, f_ana);

We can see that the numerical computation agrees rather well with the analytical solution. The largest difference between the two is found at $y = 0.5$ where $\Delta f \approx 8.3 \cdot 10^{-6}$.

The fixed point iteration algorithm has been implemented and can be found below. Additionally, the resulting figures and discussion are found below that.

In [63]:
MAX_ITER = 200
ACCURACY = 1E-8
diag = -2 * np.ones(N-2)
off_diag = np.ones(N-3)

A = lambda f, fn, dx: np.sign(fn[round(N/2)] * f[round(N/2)]) * np.sqrt(np.trapz(f**2, dx=dx) / np.trapz(fn**2, dx=dx))
cn = lambda f, fp, dx: np.trapz((f - fp)**2, dx=dx) / np.trapz(f**2, dx=dx)

matrix = SparseTridiagonal()
matrix.decompose(diag, off_diag)

# Preallocate the previous result
fp = np.ones(len(f)) * 100
diff_list = []
cn_list = []

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 2*5.5))
plt.subplot(211)

i = 0
while cn(f, fp, dy) >= ACCURACY and i < MAX_ITER:
    fp = f
    g = -1 * np.pi**2 * f
    f = matrix.solve(dy**2 * g[1:-1])
    f = np.array([0, *f, 0])

    diff_list.append(A(f_ana, f, dy) * f - f_ana)
    cn_list.append(cn(f, fp, dy))
    plt.plot(y, f, '.', ms=1.5, label=f"Iter {i+1}")

    i += 1

plt.xlabel("y")
plt.ylabel("f")
plt.legend()
plt.subplot(212)
[plt.plot(y, df, '.', ms=1.5, label=f"Iter {i+1}") for i, df in enumerate(diff_list)]
plt.xlabel("y")
plt.ylabel(r"Scaled $\Delta f$")
plt.legend()

print(f"Iterations: {i}")
print(f"Max scaled difference: {np.max(np.abs(diff_list[-1])):.3e}")

Iterations: 9
Max scaled difference: 1.533e-05

From the figure we can see that the algorithm improves the result of $f$ drastically with every iteration. Even though we have used completely random initial values, the iteration algorithm is stable enough to converge towards a result. Here though, we find an issue: the result for $f$ does not match the value we would analytically expect. We need to scale it using $A_n$ in order for the result to be correct, but that relies on knowing the result which defeats the purpose anyway, or we must normalise to $1$. In the difference plot then, because we scale the numerical result, it looks like the result is fairly accurate and becomes more accurate with every iteration. We can also see that $f_n$ starts following the expected shape much more closely as more iterations are ran.

Part 2: Screening project 2 - Self-consistent Polarisation Field¶

Question 7¶

a.¶

We have $\boldsymbol{T} = \boldsymbol{0}$, so that means we must solve $\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}\boldsymbol{m} = \boldsymbol{f}$. This allows us to compute $\epsilon_P = -\frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{f}^\dagger\boldsymbol{m}$. Now, the inverse of $\boldsymbol{A}$ is relatively simple in this problem, since it is block-diagonal in the components $\boldsymbol{\alpha}_i$. Additionally, due to the definition $\alpha_{i, ab} = \alpha\delta_{ab}$, we can see that $\boldsymbol{A}$ and its inverse are diagonal, becoming $\alpha\boldsymbol{I}$ and $\frac{1}{\alpha}\boldsymbol{I}$ respectively. If we fill this in into the expression for the polarisation energy we get, \begin{align*} \epsilon_P = -\frac{\alpha}{2}\boldsymbol{f}^T\boldsymbol{f}, \end{align*} which is component-wise identical to eq. (4.21) of the lecture notes.

Let us now consider the units of $\epsilon_P$. We know that $(4\pi\epsilon_0)^{-1}$ has units $\text{Vnm / e}$ (which can be obtained from the SI units by replacing $m = 10^9 nm$ and $e = 1.602*10^{-19}C$). From the E-field eq. (4.18) we get the following units, \begin{align*} E^0 = \frac{[V][nm]}{[e]} \cdot \frac{[e][nm]}{[nm]^3} = \frac{[V]}{[nm]}. \end{align*} This is what we would expect. Now, we must also convert the polarisability $\alpha$ to SI units, since it is currently expressed related to its cgs units $cm^3$. In SI units, $\alpha' = 4\pi\epsilon_0 \alpha$, so $\alpha' = [nm]^2 [e] / [V]$. Filling this in into the expression of $\epsilon_P$, \begin{align*} \epsilon_P = \frac{[nm]^2 [e]}{[V]} \cdot \frac{[V]^2}{[nm]^2} = [eV], \end{align*} which is a valid unit of energy.

Let us now compute the polarisation energy as a function of the amount of molecules. The code and resulting figures are found below. There, we will also discuss the results further.

In [65]:
from scpf import *
from scipy.stats import linregress as fit

alpha = 0.08 * 1/Const.INV_E0
d = 1

ep = np.zeros(10)
nd = np.zeros(len(ep))

for Nprime in range(1, 11):
    grid = Grid(Nprime, d*np.sqrt(2))
    charged = grid.get_charged_molecule()

    f = -Const.INV_E0 * np.array([i.diff(charged)[b.value] / i.dist_to(charged)**3 if i != charged else 0 for i in grid.molecules() for b in Direction])

    ep[Nprime - 1] = -alpha / 2 * f@f
    nd[Nprime - 1] = len(f)

slope, intercept, *args = fit(nd ** (-1/3), ep)

plt.plot(nd ** (-1/3), ep, '.')
plt.xlabel(r"$N_D^{-\frac{1}{3}}$")
plt.ylabel(r"$\epsilon_P \; [eV]$")
print(f"The polarisation energy at infinite N_D is {intercept:.2f} eV.")

The polarisation energy at infinite N_D is -1.47 eV.

From the Python code we can see that $\epsilon_P(N_D\rightarrow \infty) = -1.47 eV$. The reason that the polarisation energy is linear in $N_D^{-1/3}$ is twofold. Firstly, as the amount of molecules increases, the polarisation energy will move further and further towards its bulk value, meaning that every added molecule has less effect. This is because these added molecules will be further and further away from the charged molecule. In 1D, this scales as $1/r^2$, or as $1/N_D$, so by plotting the inverse of $N_D$ we are linearising this behaviour. Secondly, we compensate for the fact that molecules are added in three dimensions instead of one. This is because the previously stated decay in 3D behaves more like $1/r^6$, or $1/N_D^3$.

b.¶

The ad-hoc iterative scheme has been implemented below. The results will be discussed below that.

In [154]:
import itertools as it

def ad_hoc(Nprime, gamma, alpha_, MAX_ITER=25, plot=True):
    TOL = 1E-4
    DAMPING = gamma

    alpha = alpha_ * 1/Const.INV_E0
    grid = Grid(Nprime, d*np.sqrt(2))
    charged = grid.get_charged_molecule()

    shape = (grid.size, 3)
    m = np.zeros(shape)
    n = 1
    directions = np.array(list(it.product(range(3), range(3))))
    delta = directions[:, 0] == directions[:, 1]

    f, coords = grid.flatten()
    f = f.reshape(shape)

    ep_now = -995
    ep_prev = -999
    ep = []

    while n < MAX_ITER and np.abs(ep_now - ep_prev) >= TOL:
        #print(n)
        ep_prev = ep_now

        temp = alpha * f

        for ii, i in enumerate(grid.molecules()):
            diff = coords - i.pos
            dist = np.linalg.norm(diff, axis=1)
            prefix = Const.INV_E0 / dist**5
            prefix[ii] = 0

            t_diff = diff[:, directions[:, 0]]*diff[:, directions[:, 1]]
            t_dist = np.tile(delta, (len(dist), 1)) * np.tile(dist[:]**2, (9, 1)).T
            t_sum = np.sum(np.tile(prefix[:], (9, 1)).T * (3*t_diff - t_dist) * m[:, directions[:, 1]], axis=0)

            temp[ii, :] += alpha * np.sum(t_sum.reshape((3,3)), axis=1)

        m = (1 - DAMPING) * m + DAMPING * temp

        ep_now = -0.5 * np.sum(f * m)
        ep.append(ep_now)

        n += 1

    if plot:
        plt.plot(range(len(ep)), ep)
        plt.xlabel("Iterations")
        plt.ylabel(r"$\epsilon_P \; [eV]$")
        plt.title(f"SCPF Ad-Hoc iterative, alpha = {alpha_} nm^3")

    return ep[-1], grid.size

First, let us perform a run with $\alpha = 0.08 nm^3$ and no damping.

In [155]:
ad_hoc(1, 1, 0.08);

From this figure we see that around 18 iterations were needed for convergence, but that the system is stable. Now, let us compare to $\alpha = 0.11 nm^3$.

In [156]:
ad_hoc(1, 1, 0.11, 50);

We can clearly observe that the scheme now doesn't converge: it is unstable and we hit our iteration limit. In order to solve this, a damping parameter can be introduced. We will however do this for the $\alpha = 0.08 nm^3$ case however.

In [157]:
ad_hoc(1, 0.9, 0.08);

Now, with a damping factor $\gamma = 0.9$, we have significantly cut down on the amount of iterations required in order to satisfy the convergence criterion.

c.¶

Even though I have spent too many hours on optimising the iteration, it still runs like hot garbage. I have vectorised as much as possible, except for the iteration over all the molecules themselves. Doing that however would negate all the memory benefits of not storing $\boldsymbol{T}$, since that would basically be doing the same. Precalculating $\boldsymbol{T}$ does speed up the algorithm dramatically, but the assignment explicitly states not to do that. I would argue however that precalculating $\boldsymbol{T}$ and storing it in RAM or on-disk should pose no problem, because when one wants to compute for very large $N'$, clusters must be used for which data needs to be split up, stored and transmitted over networks anyway. Additionally, I cannot employ the power of Numba's JIT compiler since I am running Python 3.9, which isn't yet supported as of writing.

In short, I will be running up to and including $N' = 6$. The code and results are found and discussed below

From the results we can see that the extrapolated polarisation energy $\epsilon_P(N_D\rightarrow\infty) = -1.76 eV$, which is about $0.29 eV$ lower than the case where we set $\boldsymbol{T} = 0$. From the limited amount of data points is it not possible to say with a reasonable degree of accuracy if the plot of the polarisation energy is linear or has an exponential behaviour. The assumption for the extrapolation was that it is linear, as is the case in a). The difference compared to a) comes from the fact that the charged molecule influences the molecules around it, namely that dipoles are induced onto the non-charged molecules. These induced dipoles in turn then generate their own contribution to the total electric field. It is this contribution term that was ignored previously.

The runtime results found in the execution time plot resemble that of $O(N_D^2)$. Indeed when plotting $\sqrt{t}$ versus $N_D$ the plot looks linear, but again more data points would increase the accuracy of this statement. Compared to LU factorisation, which executes in $O(N_D^3)$, our execution seems faster. However, in practise I presume that the LU factorisation algorithms found in libraries are much faster than the algorithm that I have written. Indeed, there are many much smarter people out there that have already invented the most optimised wheel, whereas I have made a square one here. However, by precalculating more data (or by using rainbow tables) as I have discussed previously, we can at least decrease the scaling of the execution time (decrease $C$ in $O(C\cdot N_D^3)$), or possibly decrease the order as well.

        temp_list[n - 1, :] = temp.flatten() - m.flatten()
        K = np.zeros((n, n))
        for aa in range(n):
            for bb in range(n):
                K[aa, bb] = temp_list[aa, :] @ temp_list[bb, :]

        cn_prime = lu_solve(lu_factor(K), np.ones(n))
        lambda_ = 1 / np.sum(cn_prime)
        cn = lambda_ * cn_prime

        m = (1 - DAMPING) * m + DAMPING * (cn@(temp_list[:n] + m_list[:n])).reshape(m.shape)
        m_list[n, :] = m.flatten()

        ep_now = -0.5 * np.sum(f * m)
        ep.append(ep_now)

        n += 1

    if plot:
        plt.plot(range(len(ep)), ep)
        plt.xlabel("Iterations")
        plt.ylabel(r"$\epsilon_P \; [eV]$")
        plt.title(f"SCPF Pulay iterative, alpha = {alpha_} nm^3")

    return ep[-1], grid.size

Question 9¶

a.¶

From the lecture notes, we are lead to believe that \begin{align*} E_g = IP - EA - 2\epsilon_P. \end{align*}

Filling in the values obtained from the assignment, and using the polarisation energy $\epsilon_P = 1.76eV$ obtained from question 7c, we get, \begin{align*} E_g = 7.58 - 2.68 - 2*1.76 = 1.38 eV. \end{align*}

This value is significantly smaller than that measured by experiment, so we can conclude that the SCPF model is not appropriate to determine the band gap of $C_{60}$. Either that or the model that has been constructed is invalid, which wouldn't surprise me.
